189&nbsp;countries have agreed to the terms of the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons, which prohibits production and acquisition of nuclear weapon s while allowing peaceful development of nuclear energy.&nbsp; 
&nbsp; 
Five states are not parties to this treaty: India, Israel, North Korea, Pakistan, and South Sudan.

The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) is a UN specialized agency, created in 1944 under the (Chicago) Convention on International Civil Aviation (Chicago Convention). &nbsp; 
ICAO works with the Convention&rsquo;s 191 Signatory States and global industry and aviation organizations to develop international Standards and Recommended Practices (SARPs) which are used by States to institute legally-binding national civil aviation regulations. 
There are currently over 10,000 SARPs reflected in the 19 Annexes to the Chicago Convention which ICAO oversees, and it is through these SARPs and ICAO&rsquo;s complementary policy, auditing and capacity-building efforts that today&rsquo;s global air transport network is able to operate over 100,000 daily flights, safely, efficiently and securely in every region of the world. &nbsp;

These are the member states of the Executive Board of UNESCO &ndash; the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization.&nbsp; 
&nbsp; 
The Executive Board is responsible for the overall management of UNESCO and ensures that the decisions made by all of its member countries are put into place properly.&nbsp;

The ten countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) seek economic prosperity and stability in the region.&nbsp; 
The U.S. is not a formal member of the ASEAN but has an Ambassador posted to ASEAN to help ensure American interests are protected. 
